   216	- **Order types:** Combined taxonomy — KBM's named types (Direct Bill, Intermarket, Intuit Work from Home, Government) integrated into Pivot's specialized-order-type framework
   217	- **Invoice schedule templates:** Pivot's framework (50/40/10, 30/40/30, 100% prepay, custom variations; up to 5 standard templates)
   218	- **Template management:** Self-service via PDF Composer with merged-company design ownership (KBM's Kipp-pattern)
   219	- **Tax overrides:** Manual override capability for government and MillerKnoll-direct-bill orders
   220	- **MillerKnoll integrations:** Combined suite (ServiceNet, ServiceTime, Quote Tool, Order Manager); Coupa evaluation deferred to Realize-phase ROI analysis
   221	- **Tiered pricing escalation:** Retained as merged-company business issue with cross-organization commercial ownership
   222	- **Commission:** Header-level with split-percentage (CRM-locked); line-level commissionable flag; storage fees always commissionable
   223	- **SIF/BOM import:** Standard via Smart Table grouping
   224	- **Acknowledgements:** Standard automation
   225	- **PO generation:** Vendor splitting, acknowledgement processing, transmission per Pivot framework
   226	
   227	Net read: the merged-company Order Management combines design choices that fit the merged-company's situation. Pivot's contributions reflect its invoice schedule template depth, PDF Composer infrastructure, MillerKnoll Order Manager integration framework, and process-flow orientation. KBM's contributions reflect its operational specifics — named approval thresholds, customer PO tracking framework, order-type taxonomy with volumes, self-service template ownership pattern, ServiceNet/ServiceTime/Coupa integration paths, and the MillerKnoll tiered-pricing escalation. The merged company benefits from both — Pivot's process infrastructure becomes the operational baseline; KBM's operational specifics become the implementation detail.
